@node Stage commit and push
@section Stage, commit, and push

@findex magit-extras-stage-commit-and-push
The most common Git workflow---stage modifications, write a commit message, and push---typically requires several separate steps in Magit. The command @code{magit-extras-stage-commit-and-push} collapses this into a single action. When called interactively, it first displays the unstaged diff for review, then prompts for a commit message.

The command accepts two optional arguments. When FILE is non-nil, only that file is staged rather than all modified files. When NO-PUSH is non-nil, the push step is skipped, which is useful when you want to batch several commits before pushing. The command is adapted from a workflow by Sacha Chua.

@findex magit-extras-stage-commit-and-push-all-repos
For users who maintain multiple Git repositories, @code{magit-extras-stage-commit-and-push-all-repos} iterates over all directories listed in @code{paths-dir-all-repos} and performs a ``midnight update'' on each one. This is intended for automated, periodic synchronization---for example, from a timer or a shutdown hook. Each repository receives a commit with the message ``Midnight update''.

@findex magit-extras-with-editor-finish-and-push
When composing a commit message in a @samp{with-editor} buffer, you may want to finalize and push immediately. The command @code{magit-extras-with-editor-finish-and-push} calls @code{with-editor-finish} to complete the editing session and then invokes @code{magit-push-current-to-pushremote} to push the new commit.

@node Tag and submodule checkout
@section Tag and submodule checkout

@findex magit-extras-checkout-tag-with-submodules
Projects that use Git submodules often need to check out a specific tag consistently across the main repository and all submodules. The command @code{magit-extras-checkout-tag-with-submodules} prompts for a tag (or the ``main'' branch) via @code{completing-read} and then performs a force checkout.

When ``main'' is selected, the command checks out the @samp{main} branch in every submodule recursively and pulls the latest changes. When a tag is selected, it resets all submodules to match the commit recorded in the superproject and reinitializes them. This distinction ensures that tag checkouts produce a deterministic state while branch checkouts pull the latest upstream changes.

@node Dirty repository detection
@section Dirty repository detection

@findex magit-extras-warn-if-repo-is-dirty
@findex magit-extras-repo-is-dirty-p
Before performing automated operations on a repository, it is often wise to verify that it has no uncommitted changes. The command @code{magit-extras-warn-if-repo-is-dirty} checks whether the repository at REPO-PATH (or the current repository if nil) has any modifications and emits an alert via the @samp{alert} package if so.

The predicate @code{magit-extras-repo-is-dirty-p} performs the underlying check using @code{magit-anything-modified-p}. It returns @code{t} when the directory exists, is a Git repository, and contains uncommitted changes. Both functions are useful in hooks or timers that perform automated Git operations.

@node Dispatch menu
@section Dispatch menu

@findex magit-extras-dispatch
The function @code{magit-extras-dispatch} defines a customized transient prefix that replaces the default @code{magit-dispatch} via @samp{advice-add}. The layout largely mirrors the standard Magit dispatch but includes the Forge dispatch under @samp{n} and a push binding under @samp{.}, among other adjustments. The menu is organized into three groups: transient and DWIM commands, applying changes (visible only in Magit buffers), and essential commands.

Because this function overrides @code{magit-dispatch}, invoking the standard Magit dispatch keybinding will display this custom menu.

